1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,403
Engram is a memory engine for AI agents, built on Qwen Cloud. It decides what to remember, what to recall, what to forget, and what to stop believing.

2
00:00:10,467 --> 00:00:19,801
Tell the agent something that matters. A Qwen importance score decides whether it becomes a typed memory, and you watch it land on the board.

3
00:00:19,867 --> 00:00:28,133
A brand new session starts empty, but Engram recalls that preference under a hard token budget, and the agent answers with it.

4
00:00:28,200 --> 00:00:37,023
Small talk scores low and is deliberately not stored. Every engine decision is visible, including the ones it declines to make.

5
00:00:37,100 --> 00:00:48,385
Change your mind, and qwen 3.7 plus adjudicates the conflict. The old fact is superseded with a full audit trail, never silently overwritten.

6
00:00:48,433 --> 00:00:57,768
Memories that go unused decay on an Ebbinghaus curve and drop out of recall. Timely forgetting is built in, not bolted on.

7
00:00:57,833 --> 00:01:09,722
Sixty six unit tests, an MCP server so any agent can plug in, and the backend on Alibaba Cloud. Engram: memory that behaves like memory should.
